snippet.textDisplay:
I know they were trying to move away from the story being focused on Anakin/Vader but I really think more references to him would have been really cool in this saga. We see the melted Vader helmet a LOT these past three episodes and nothing really came about it. Vader was Kylo's dark-side role model and it would have been really cool to see Kylo experience some Vader hologram/vision scene and Rey have an Anakin hologram scene at the end. Even in the scene on Ahch-to with Luke's hologram, when she was expressing her fear of being a Palpatine and going to the Dark Side, Luke just as easily could have have related to her with his father being Vader.


Like it or not Star Wars is built with Anakin Skywalker at the epicenter and even though he is long gone I think paying homage to him with more references could have made some of the scenes more powerful, his legend was still quite prominent in this story and I don't think referencing him more would have taken any attention away from the current story.

I loved the film. I think as fans we tend to over analyse the content which is why we see the originals as the best. We were too young to do all that over thinking we had a blank sheet. Instead we just watched, as children did this movie.

We are world wise, slightly jaded and no film could ever stand up to the film in our heads, the film we want or indeed demand.

So I sat there Friday with my wife and the second the music and crawl started I was transformed into the 8 year old me and I had a rollercoaster of a ride... just my opinion.

snippet.textDisplay: The Last Jedi has some problems, but it was great. It tried much harder to make statements inside the Star Wars universe that can be universally understood and add complexity to the stories. Namely, Johnson seemed to address three questions/problems that have become inherent to the Skywalker saga: the lack of democracy or meritocracy in the force (apparently you need to be a Skywalker or a Palpatine to be strong enough in the Force to be discovered), the over-reliance on a young cocky guy to fix stuff by shooting first (there’s one Han Solo, Poe should have been his own character), and the childish light side vs dark side simplicity of its morality (the Force seeks balance, which implies that it should be more complex, like life is). Rise of Skywalker abandons that for simple statements in a film that’s stitched together to try to tell a coherent episodic story while bringing the whole saga to a close, retconning/ignoring TLJ, and apologizing to a chunk of the fanbase that didn’t appreciate the last movie, partially due to the fact that all this stuff that people knew about alike was deemed Legends and they wanted the sequel trilogy to he was close to that as possible. All of this is papered over by action sequences (some of them very God mode-sequel) to never let it slow down and have much emotional weight. JJ Abrams is a pretty derivative filmmaker but this isn’t even him at his derivative best.

I really enjoyed the film, but it does have issues in it which are kind of present throughout the trilogy. I've made an analogy that kind of sums up this trilogy, which I call "The Mash Potato Dinner Party" and it goes like this:

JJ Abrams has a load of people round and gives them all extremely small portions of some mashed potato that he's made. Half of the people there say things like "This is amazing, can I have some more of this?" and "What's your secret?" He replies with a smile "There'll be more of this coming as the evening progresses and I'll tell you all about my secret method later" Whereas others are saying "This is no different to any mash I've ever tasted before, in fact, it's exactly the same as the mash I always have. This is so unoriginal" He then realises they are low on drinks, so goes out to purchase some more and asks his housemate, Rian Johnson, to watch over the guests.



Rian Johnson then enters the room and scrapes JJ's mash into the bin, and when there isn't enough room for it all, he throws the rest out of the window, into the garden. He then presents the guests with bowls of porridge that have orange juice, chocolate and lard all mixed in it. Some of the guests are saying "Wow, this is so different and is like nothing I've ever tried before, I loved it" and "This is great because we were only expecting mash and this has really surprised me" Or, 'subverted my expectations', you might say 😉 Others are saying "What about JJ's mash? and what's his secret?" Rian responds "We aren't having mash anymore and there's no secret, it was just store bought" People then start complaining, saying the food is disgusting and Rian responds with things like "You just don't know good food" and "You're just ungrateful, if you don't like it then get out of my house" He then receives a phone call and leaves the room, when JJ returns.



He tells everyone that someone phoned him telling him what Rian had done, so he went around asking everyone's families how they liked their mash and he has now made 10 different types and has also bought some ready made stuff. Instead of asking each guest how they like it, he's just piling bits of every mash on everyone's plates. Whilst doing this, he also takes the porridge Rian made off everyone's plates, even off the plates of the guests who liked it! He also scrapes the potato Rian threw away out of the bin and out of the garden, dumping them on people's plates too. He then adds double the amount of milk and butter to his own mash, which he also dollops on their plates as well. He doesn't even give people time to finish the mash already on their plates, before shoving even more on them. He also spends the remainder of the evening telling people what the method for his mash was, before giving them all a laminated piece of paper each with it written on to take home. Some of them leave only liking JJ's mash, some only liked Rian's porridge, some got annoyed with the inconsistency of the evening and others enjoyed the whole thing, but it was ruined by others complaining, meaning no one walked away completely satisfied.

Just watched it yesterday and my take it this:

1. It’s very entertaining, enjoyable and visually stunning, technical masterpiece with a musical score that’s an instant classic. In other words it’s a VERY WELL DONE Star Wars movie.

However, with Palpatine returning, than the whole prophecy wasn’t truly fulfilled. Or it was misinterpreted. Because it’s seems that the only part and purpose that Vader really had in the entire saga was to kill off the “original” Palpatine and allow him to evolve into his “next” stage, and to brith Luke and Leia which Leia gives birth to Kylo who is essential in helping Rey defeat the emperor. It all just seems to fall apart from there. I don’t believe the saga would have ended this way had it NOT been for the disaster that The Last Jedi was.
